Examples for WebService::OCI
============================

These scripts use the DEFAULT profile from ~/.oci/config unless noted.
See WebService::OCI::Guide for how to set that up, and
WebService::OCI::Cookbook for more recipes.

  first-call.pl
      Hello world: print your Object Storage namespace.
        perl eg/first-call.pl

  whoami.pl [--config FILE] [--profile DEFAULT]
      Show the authenticated user and tenancy (Identity API) - a fuller
      config check than the namespace ping.

  discover.pl --compartment OCID [--shape NAME] [--os "Oracle Linux"]
      List availability domains, the shapes offered in each, and recent
      images - handy when a shape/image is rejected or out of capacity.

  list-instances.pl <compartment-ocid> [profile]
      List Compute instances in a compartment, following pagination.
      The root compartment OCID is your tenancy OCID.

  objectstorage.pl <compartment-ocid> <bucket> [file]
      Namespace + list buckets; optionally upload a file and read it back
      (shows the PutObject signing exception).

  object-sync.pl --bucket NAME --dir PATH [--prefix STR]
      Upload a directory to a bucket: list existing objects (paginated),
      then upload any local file not already there.

  raw-request.pl METHOD SERVICE PATH [key=value ...]
      A minimal generic caller, e.g.
        perl eg/raw-request.pl GET iaas /20160918/instances compartmentId=ocid1..c

  setup-network.pl --compartment OCID [--name demo] [...]
      Create a minimal public network over the API: VCN, internet gateway,
      a default route to it, and a public regional subnet. Prints the subnet
      OCID to feed to launch-instance.pl. (Networking resources are free.)

  launch-instance.pl --compartment OCID --subnet OCID --ssh-key FILE [...]
      Launch a Compute instance end to end: resolve availability domain and
      image, launch, wait for RUNNING, print the public IP and ssh command.

  teardown.pl --compartment OCID [--instance OCID] [--vcn OCID]
      Clean up: terminate an instance and/or delete a VCN (subnets and
      internet gateways first, then the VCN).

For the command-line tool, see: oci-rest --help
